1 Introduction

The following case study has been developed to illustrate the merits of microarray analysis as a hypothesis-generating tool. By working through this exercise you will learn how to complete a microarray analysis from start to finish. This process involves converting raw data produced by microarray scanners into lists of differentially expressed genes and eventually arriving at biological interpretations of these lists.

All analyses will be carried out with the free statistics and graphics software R (R Development Core Team 2008) and the software package limma which implements mathematical functions for the analysis of two color microarrays (Smyth 2005). Using R has two major advantages: first, it is available to everyone at no cost and second, it provides a very flexible framework for microarray analyses. In this module, ready-to-execute R code will be provided, since its purpose is not the teaching of programming in R but a demonstration of the utility of R for microarray analysis. Despite providing the code we encourage students to familiarize themselves with R and to decipher the meaning of our scripts.

This case study has been adapted from a published microarray experiment (Schmidt et al. 2005). The data were part of herbivory study carried out to compare the defense responses of two solanaceous plants, Nicotiana attenuata and Solanum nigrum, to attack by shared herbivores (here Manduca sexta). In that study, cDNA from both plant species had been hybridized to a cDNA microarray representing 15,264 Solanum tuberosum unigenes (the potato chip). S. tuberosum, the potato plant, is also a member of the nightshade family (Solanaceae). Thus, micorarrays developed for the potato plant can be used to study species in the same plant family given appropriate caution and controls.

For this case study, four treatments of the original experiment were selected (figure 1), consisting of plants either exposed or not exposed to one day of herbivore feeding.

Figure1: Experimental set up. The experiment consisted of four treatments resulting four sources of RNA: NM – N. attenuata attacked by M. sexta for 1 day. NC – N. attenuata unattacked for 1 day. SM – S. nigrum attacked by M. sexta for 1 day. SC – S. nigrum unattacked for 1 day.

Total RNA was extracted from the foliage of the four groups of plants, reverse-transcribed into cDNA and labelled with the fluorescent dyes Cy3 and Cy5. Cy3-labled cDNA from herbivore-induced plants was competitively hybridized with Cy5-labled cDNA from non-induced plants and each treatment was replicated thrice thus resulting in a total of 6 independent hybridizations (figure 2).

Figure 2: Hybridization scheme. Each arrow represents one microarray. Herbivore-induced tissue (cy3) was co-hybridized with control tissue (cy5).

The module consists of two parts. In the first part, you will determine which genes are up- and down-regulated in each species through a guided step by step execution of an R script. In particular, we will explain how to pre-process and normalize the raw data and how to apply statistical procedures to these transformed data to call differentially expressed genes. We will also introduce graphical tools frequently used in presentation and publications of microarray studies (global gene expression). The second part focuses on the biological interpretation of the results through R scripts that allow enrichment tests of gene sets (gene ontologies) and a guide to online resources which allow you to research differentially expressed genes of your choice.

You will be working on iMacs in the physics lab (SC5.15). Ideally you work on the same computer in both labs as you will be using files created in lab 1 for lab 2. Log on to the Bioinformatics account (password: IMBSTeaching). R and the required libraries are installed. You will also have access to Excel. All data are saved in the ‘case study’ folder in the Bioinformatics device. Before you begin, drag and drop the complete ‘case study’ folder to your desktop. Files that you generate during the analysis will be written into the same folder. Data contained in the case study folder include:

  • Raw data: 2450.gpr, 2455.gpr, 2460.gpr, 2465.gpr, 2470.gpr, 2475.gpr
  • Scripts: case study script.R, gse test.R
  • Supporting files: targetsherb.txt, find.txt, potato_gomatrix.txt
  • Graphs: MA plots folder, density plots folder, box plots folder, spatial plots folder

2 First step in R

R is a freely available statistics and graphics software that is widely used in bioinformatics. The main advantage is that scientists themselves constantly add to it by programming new software packages that run in the R environment and that R is constantly updated too. As a rule of thumb there is a package for any genome analysis job you would like to get done. To be able to take advantage of the wealth of R-based packages you need to familiarize yourself with some basic R procedures and not be afraid to use a command line interface.

To get started, launch RStudio . Commands can be typed directly into the Console or alternatively in the Editor. The latter has the advantage that a collection of commands (called a script) can be saved and thus re-run and modified later. To execute commands from the editor, highlight the command and click CTRL+Return. Apart from commands, a script often contains comments of various kinds. Comments are preceded by the # sign which prevents R to try and execute them.

3 Step by step Microarray analysis

library(limma)

3.2 Inspect one of the raw data files in Excel.

Open one of the raw data files (.gpr, generated by the image analysis software) in Excel and look at the raw data. Each file represents one array. It contains foreground and background intensities for the red (F635, B635) and the green (F532, B532) channel for each spot on the array plus annotation to unambiguously identify each spot. The foreground is an overall measure of the intensity of the spot while the background is a measure of the ambient signal. Background fluorescence can arise from many sources, such as non-specific binding of labelled sample to the array surface, processing effects such as deposits left after the wash stage or optical noise from the scanner. Most image analysis programs return local background intensities, obtained from the mean or median of the pixel intensity values surrounding each spot.

Figure 3: Spatial image and simplified version of a raw data file generated by a microarray scanner. Left panel: Spatial image of overlay of red and green channel of the potato cDNA array. The grid consists of 48 blocks each of which consists of 26 columns and 26 rows amounting to a total of 32,448 spots. Not all spots contain DNA. Right panel: A ‘.gpr’ file is generated for each array. It contains the following main information for each spot: coordinates on the array, mean and median foreground and background signal intensities of the red (wave length 635) and the green (wave length 532) channel, gene identifier, gene description and other annotation.

3.4 Background correction.

Microarray data must be background corrected to remove the effects of non-specific binding or spatial heterogeneity across the array. Background correction can be done by different methods. To simply subtract the background from the foreground signal has been found to result in too many false discoveries in the end. Limma provides a method called normexp. It performs well and results in strictly positive adjusted signal intensities.

#necessary to eliminate unspecific flourescence
#create new object RG.b using the previously created RG object
RG.b <- backgroundCorrect(RG, method="normexp", offset=50)
## Array 1 corrected
## Array 2 corrected

3.6 Transform data

Usually, logarithms to base 2 are taken from the red and green signal intensities of each array. This leads to an even spread of the data across the intensity range, similar variability at most intensity levels and a bell-shaped distribution of intensities. Then, M and A values are calculated, which are defined as follows:

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} M = log_2(Cy_5/Cy_3) = Log_2(Cy_5) - log(Cy_3) \\ A = (log_2(Cy_5) + log_2(Cy_3)) / 2 = \frac{log_2(Cy_5 * Cy_3)}{2} \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

Log fold ratios are preferred because they have a natural symmetry that reflects the biology that is not present in the raw fold ratio (cy5 signal/cy3 signal). For example, the raw fold ratio of 2-fold up-regulated genes, genes that are not differentially expressed and genes that are 2-fold up-regulated are 2, 1, and 0.5, respectively, but the log fold ratios are 1, 0 and -1, respectively.

#this is done to ensure an even spread of the data and similar variation across all intensities
#the M value (log fold ratio) is defined like this: log2(intensity of the red signal/intensity of the green signal) 
#the A value (average log intensities) is defined like this: (log2(intensity of the red signal) + log2(intensity of the green signal))/2. 
RG.n <- normalizeWithinArrays(RG.f, method="none")

Plot the data to see the effect of the log function on the data distribution.

plot(RG$G,RG$R)

hist(RG$G)

plot(log2(RG$G),log2(RG$R))

hist(log2(RG$G))

Check how $R and $G are gone from the RG.n object and $M and $A have been added to the RG.n object by comparing the first three genes of the first array in objects RG.f and RG.n

RG.f[1:3,1]
RG.n[1:3,1]

3.7 Within-array normalization

Normalization is required to remove any systematic trends which arise from the microarray technology rather than from differences between the RNA samples hybridized to the array. Within-array normalization is needed to remove bias associated with a) different responses of the green and the red channel and b) intensity differences across different areas of an array (spatial bias). To achieve this, a non-linear regression (loess) of the M values against the A values is performed. The normalized M-values are calculated by subtracting the M values fitted on the regression from the raw M values.

Graphs: Compare the MA plots for each of the six microarrays before and after within array normalization that are provided in the MA plots folder.

#this is done to remove experimental variability that stems from using two different dyes
#fit a non-linear regression (called loess) of the M values to the A values
#to obtain normalized M values the fitted M values will be subtracted from the un-normalized M values 
MA <- normalizeWithinArrays(RG.n, method="loess") 
#check the effect of within array normalization on M and A values
#by looking at the first three genes of the first array in the RG.n object
#and the newly created MA object
RG.n$M[1:3,1]
MA$M[1:3,1]
RG.n$A[1:3,1]
MA$A[1:3,1]
#compare the MA plot before and after lowess normalization
plotMA(RG.n[,1])

plotMA(MA[,1])

3.8 Between array normalization

To be able to compare samples hybridized to different arrays, it is necessary to correct for the variability introduced by using multiple arrays. Methods for between-array normalization all assume that variations in the distributions of the M-values between arrays are a result of experimental conditions and do not represent biological variability. A frequently used method is quantile normalization. Quantile normalization as implemented in limma ensures that the red and green intensities have the same empirical distribution across arrays and across channels. It changes both the M and A values when compared to the M and A values obtained after within-array normalization.

#this is done to account for experimental variation that stems from using different arrays 
#quantile normalization as implemented here equalizes the distributions of the
#red and green signal intensities across all arrays
MA.q <- normalizeBetweenArrays(MA, method="quantile")
#check the effect of between array normalization on M and A values
#by looking at the first three genes of the first array in the MA object
#and the newly created MA.q object
MA$M[1:3,1]
MA.q$M[1:3,1]
MA$A[1:3,1]
MA.q$A[1:3,1]

Use box-plots to see the effects of the normalization

boxplot(MA$A, main="Before normalization", horizontal=TRUE,las=1)

boxplot(MA.q$A, main="After normalization", horizontal=TRUE,las=1)

Remark: in a R box-plot, the whiskers are: \[ UpperWhisker = min(max(x), Q_3 + 1.5 * IQR)\\ LowerWhisker = max(min(x), Q_1 – 1.5 * IQR) \] With IQR being the Inter Quartile Range (aka. the length of the box)

Graphs: Compare the box plots of the red intensities before and after between array normalization that are provided in the box plots folder. Also, compare the density plots of the red and green intensities after background correction, after within-array normalization and after between-array normalization that are provided in the density plots folder.

3.9 Statistical analysis.

  1. First, arrange duplicate spots in consecutive rows. Then, average duplicate spots which reduces the number of spots to 11243. With the 3 following commands, fit a linear model to each of these spots.
#each gene (clone) has been spotted twice on the array
#in this step the data are sorted by clone name so that duplicate spots 
#of the same gene appear in consecutive rows
#this is needed for subsequent spot averaging
index2 <- order(MA.q$genes$"Clone_name")
MA.q <- MA.q[index2,]

#now calculate the average of replicate spots
MA.q.a <- avedups(MA.q, ndups=2, spacing=1) #weighted average
#check how the number of spots was halfed by this step by comparing the dimensions of the
#MA.q object with the dimensions of the MA.q.a object
dim(MA.q)
dim(MA.q.a)
  1. Call function lmFit. A linear model is fitted to the expression data for each spot. Expression ratios (=coefficients) are calculated according to the design matrix and stored in object fit1.
fit1 <- lmFit(MA.q.a, design)
## Warning: Partial NA coefficients for 1731 probe(s)
#check the dimensions of fit1
dim(fit1)

#look at expression coefficients for the first three genes
fit1$coefficients[1:3,]
  1. Next, call function contrasts.fit. Expression ratios (coefficients) are calculated for each comparison specified in the contrast matrix.
fit2 <- contrasts.fit(fit1, cont.matrix)
#check the dimensions of fit2
dim(fit2)

#look at expression coefficients for the first three genes
#the first two are identical to the expression coefficients in fit1
fit2$coefficients[1:3,]
  1. Then, call function eBayes. With this function, moderated t-statistics, a moderated F-statistic, p-values for both the t- and F-statistics and log odds for differential expression are calculated for each spot. The moderated t-statistics test whether or not log fold expression ratios (M-values) are significantly different from zero (this is done for all 3 comparisons separately). On the other hand, the moderated F-statistic tests if any of the 3 separate M values were significantly different from zero. The F-statistic is an overall test computed from the set of t-statistics for that gene.
fit3 <- eBayes(fit2)

Show t-statistics with p-value of differential expression for the first three genes

3.10 Call differentially expressed genes

Use the decideTests function to call differentially expressed genes based on a combination of thresholds for adjusted p-values (0.05) and M values (-0.58 < M < 0.58). Applying the summary function to the results object will show you numbers of differentially expressed genes for each of the three comparisons.

#given the log2 scale this includes genes with M>0.58 and M<-0.58 
#p-values have been adjusted for multiple testing using the default
#adjustment implemented in 'decideTests': BH (Benjamini-Hochberg adjustment)
log2(1.5)
## [1] 0.5849625
results <- decideTests(fit3, lfc=log2(1.5))

3.11 Create lists of differentially expressed genes.

Save lists for each of the three comparisons by executing the loop in the following R code.

for (i in 1:3) {
  top <- topTable(fit3, coef=i, n=11243)
  top <- top[order(top$Clone_name),]
  cc <- cbind(top,results[,i])
  a <- names(cc)
  a[15] <- c("test")
  colnames(cc) <- a
  write.table(cc,(paste(i,"_all.txt",sep="")), col.names=NA, sep="\t")
  c <- cbind(top,results[,i])
  a <- names(c)
  a[15] <- c("test")
  colnames(c) <- a
  c_m1 <- c[which(c$test==-1),]
  dim(c_m1)
  write.table(c_m1, paste(i,"_down.txt",sep="") ,sep="\t", col.names=NA)
  c_m1_s <- c_m1$Clone_name
  length(c_m1_s)
  write.table(c_m1_s, paste(i,"_down_s.txt",sep="") , sep="\t", col.names=NA)
  c_p1 <- c[which(c$test==1),]
  dim(c_p1)
  write.table(c_p1, paste(i,"_up.txt",sep="") , sep="\t", col.names=NA)
  c_p1_s <- c_p1$Clone_name
  length(c_p1_s)
  write.table(c_p1_s, paste(i, "_up_s.txt",sep=""), sep="\t", col.names=NA)
}

The lists contents and file names are as follows: (1) All data: “contrast nr_all.txt” (2) Down-regulated genes: “contrast nr_down.txt” (3) Up-regulated genes: “contrast nr_up.txt” (4) Up-regulated clone names only: “contrast nr_down_s.txt” (5) Down-regulated clone names only: “contrast nr_up_s.txt”

These lists contain annotation information (first eight columns), log fold change (M value), average expression (overall A value), t-statistic, P.value, adjusted P.value, B (log odds of differential expression) and the expression score generated by the decideTests function (-1,0,+1, NA) for all genes (list 1), down-regulated genes (list 2) and up-regulated genes (list 3).

3.12 Create volcano plots.

Save volcano plots for each of the three comparisons/contrasts. Up-, down- and non-regulated genes are depicted in red, green and black, respectively. Volcano plots are a very compact and informative graphical tool to visualize the results of differential gene expression.

#create volcano plots for each of the three contrasts (NM, SM, NM-SM) by running the loop below. One of the lists you created in the previous step ('contrastnr_run1.txt')is being read back into R for this purpose.

for(j in 1:3)
{

  dim(genes.m1)
  genes.n <- genes[genes$test==0,]
  dim(genes.n)
  genes.p1 <- genes[genes$test==1,]
  dim(genes.p1)
  
  jpeg(paste(j,"_vp.jpg"),width=600, height=600)
  plot((genes[,9]),(genes[,14]), type="n", xlab="Log Fold Change", ylab="abs Log10(adj.P.value)", cex.axis=1.6, cex.lab=1.6, xlim = c(-5, 5), ylim = c(0,10))
  points((genes.m1[,9]),(genes.m1[,16]), col="green")
  points((genes.n[,9]),(genes.n[,16]), col="black")
  points((genes.p1[,9]),(genes.p1[,16]), col="red")
  abline(v=log2(1.5), lty=3)
  abline(v=-log2(1.5), lty=3)
  abline(h=0)
  abline(v=0)
  abline(h=abs(log10(0.05)), lty=3)
  dev.off()
}

5 Terms and concepts relevant to this microarray case study

  • M value: log (base 2) of the fold ratio of Cy5 intensity divided by Cy3 intensity (equal to the difference in log-intensities of Cy5 and Cy3)
  • A value: average of the log (base 2) of Cy3 and Cy5 intensities
  • MA plot: plot of log fold ratios (M, y-axis) against average log intensities (A, x-axis)
  • Density plot: plot of distribution of log2-transformed Cy5 and Cy3 intensities of all arrays
  • Box plot: Allows to visualize several distributions simultaneously. Each distribution is shown as a central box with horizontal lines known as whiskers. The line in the center of the box represents the mean, the box itself represents the standard deviation and the whiskers represent the extreme values of the distribution. The boxplot function in R uses non-parametric equivalents of the mean and the standard deviation (the median and the median absolute deviation of the median)
  • Volcano plot: The volcano plot arranges genes along dimensions of biological and statistical significance: the log fold change (M) is plotted on the x-axis while the y-axis represents statistical evidence (often a p-value on a negative log scale). The x-axis indicates biological impact of the change, the y-axis indicates the reliability of the change. The researcher needs to trade off both criteria when calling genes differentially expressed.
  • Venn Diagram: Depicts logical relations of sets. Usually up to three sets can be compared with overlapping circles. Overlapping and non-overlapping areas represent common or specific elements in the sets that are to be compared
  • Heatmap: A heatmap is a false color image with a dendrogram added on top and on the side. The top and side dendrograms represent the relationship between samples and genes, respectively and are in general created by hierarchical clustering
  • P-value: Each hypothesis test builds a probabilisitic model under the null hypothesis that there is no biological effects. Assuming that there is no effect, it is possible to calculate the probability (p-value) of observing a statistic that is at least as extreme as the statistic observed in the experimental data. Usually, a probability of less than 0.05 is considered small enough to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a biological effect. The p-value is also known as type 1 error - the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is actually true (false positive result).
  • Lods: Log-odds that the gene is differentially expressed. A lods of 1.5 means the odds of differential expression is \(exp(1.5)=4.48\) and the probability that the gene is differentially expressed is \(4.48/(1+4.48)=0.82\) or \(82\%\). Lods = 0 means a 50/50% chance that the gene is differentially expressed. Lods calculation requires a prior percentage of expected differentially expressed genes to be specified (e.g. 1%)
